John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have had a number of academic achievements, and this continues in 2018 with other excellent test results. Individual and group achievements in sports, art, music and other community activities underline this.
The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) has more than 30,000 pupils throughout Scotland, representing them with the best possible service levels for their pupils and parents.
Independent schools prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement individually adapted school education plans, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart."
It is an important observation that if we want to build relations and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely solely on English.
The latest results of this year's exams show that languages are at the top of the tables, while independent schools have the highest degree of success.
A total of 68 percent of pupils learning a foreign language achieved the best grades A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students reached the highest grade A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages such as subjects chosen by pupils are as weighted in the study plans of independent and other schools as are STEM courses (sciences, technology, technical fields and mathematics).
The survey carried out by the British Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17% of the lack of language skills is due to the reasons given by employers as problems in job vacancies.
That is why language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career you choose, if you learn a second language, you will have the real advantage of having such a lifelong skill in the future.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person speaking more languages automatically gains an advantage over competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 between 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, with the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, namely 15%, being French.
Therefore, it is important for children today to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially those of emerging economies, they will have a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child is interested in, he will always have several languages to choose from in independent schools with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing educational environments that children prepare and equip them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may be.
At this point, it cannot be denied that languages are essential for the future of the country in a global business environment, so it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
