According to the FWC, flowering water stains are now reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts – this suggests a decreasing concentration.
The flowering red tide water ranges about 130 miles from the northern district of Pinellas to the southern district of Lee.
Blurs were observed about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but last week it was already relatively fewer places.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, mean concentrations were reported off the coast or on the high seas at Pinellas County. Low to high concentrations, lowest to high concentrations in Manatee County, lowest to high concentrations in Sarasota County, lowest to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, lowest to high concentrations off the coast or on the high seas at Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County were observed in Hillsborough County.
Respiratory irritations continue to occur in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory irritation was not reported in northwest Florida last week.
